	<h2>Understanding Central Valley Wind Conditions</h2>

	<h3>Stockton Wind Climate Data</h3>
	<p>Know what your fence must withstand:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Average wind speed:</strong> 7-10 mph year-round</li>
		<li><strong>Common sustained winds:</strong> 15-25 mph during weather events</li>
		<li><strong>Regular gusts:</strong> 30-40 mph several times per year</li>
		<li><strong>Extreme events:</strong> 50-60+ mph gusts during major storms</li>
		<li><strong>Peak wind season:</strong> November through March (winter storm systems)</li>
		<li><strong>Secondary peak:</strong> March through May (spring storm systems)</li>
		<li><strong>Wind direction:</strong> Predominantly westerly and southwesterly</li>
		<li><strong>Delta breeze:</strong> Consistent summer afternoon winds 10-20 mph</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>How Wind Damages Fences</h3>
	<p>Understanding failure modes helps prevent them:</p>

	<p><strong>Post Pull-Out/Lean:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Cause:</strong> Posts set too shallow or with inadequate concrete</li>
		<li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Fence panels lean progressively in wind direction</li>
		<li><strong>Progression:</strong> Starts with slight lean, worsens with each wind event</li>
		<li><strong>Most common in:</strong> Clay soils that soften when wet</li>
		<li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Proper depth (1/3 total height minimum) and concrete mass</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Panel Blow-Out:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Cause:</strong> Solid panels create excessive wind load (sail effect)</li>
		<li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Entire panels rip away from posts</li>
		<li><strong>Progression:</strong> Sudden failure during high wind event</li>
		<li><strong>Most common in:</strong> Tall solid fences (6+ feet) with standard spacing</li>
		<li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Closer post spacing, stronger connections, wind breaks in design</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Connection Failure:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Cause:</strong> Inadequate fasteners or mounting methods</li>
		<li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Panels separate from posts at attachment points</li>
		<li><strong>Progression:</strong> Screws pull out or brackets break during sustained wind</li>
		<li><strong>Most common in:</strong> Fences using minimal or improper fasteners</li>
		<li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Proper fastener type, quantity, and placement</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Material Failure:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Cause:</strong> Wood splits, vinyl cracks, metal bends under stress</li>
		<li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Pickets break, panels crack, aluminum bends</li>
		<li><strong>Progression:</strong> Degraded materials fail at weak points</li>
		<li><strong>Most common in:</strong> Aged or low-quality materials</li>
		<li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Quality materials rated for wind loads</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Wind Load Calculations</h3>
	<p>Basic physics determining fence engineering requirements:</p>

	<p><strong>Key Factors in Wind Load:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Wind speed:</strong> Load increases with square of wind speed (50 mph = 4x force of 25 mph)</li>
		<li><strong>Fence height:</strong> Taller fences catch more wind, create greater leverage on posts</li>
		<li><strong>Panel solidity:</strong> Solid panels catch full wind; open designs let wind pass through</li>
		<li><strong>Exposure:</strong> Open areas experience higher winds than sheltered locations</li>
		<li><strong>Fence orientation:</strong> Perpendicular to prevailing wind takes maximum load</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Simplified Load Estimation:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>50 mph wind on 6-ft solid fence:</strong> ~50 lbs per linear foot of panel</li>
		<li><strong>60 mph wind on 6-ft solid fence:</strong> ~70 lbs per linear foot of panel</li>
		<li><strong>8-ft panel at 6 feet spacing:</strong> 400-560 lbs total force per panel</li>
		<li><strong>Posts must resist:</strong> Both the direct force and the leverage (moment)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Design Elements for Wind Resistance</h2>

	<h3>Post Specifications - The Critical Foundation</h3>

	<p><strong>Post Size Requirements:</strong></p>

